---
import ServicePageLayout from '../layouts/ServicePageLayout.astro';

const title = "Pet Grief Support | Coping with the Loss of a Pet | Pet Farewell";
const description = "Find compassionate resources and guidance for pet grief support. Learn how to navigate the difficult emotions of losing a beloved animal companion.";

const headline = "Pet Grief Support & Resources";
const subheadline = "You are not alone. Finding your way through the profound sorrow of losing a cherished animal companion.";

const headings = [
  { depth: 2, slug: "understanding-pet-grief", text: "Understanding Pet Grief" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "the-grieving-process", text: "The Grieving Process is Non-Linear" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "supporting-children", text: "Supporting Children Through Pet Loss" },
  { depth: 2, slug: "when-to-seek-help", text: "When to Seek Professional Help" }
];

const faqItems = [
  {
    question: "Is it normal to grieve this deeply for an animal?",
    answer: "Absolutely. For many people, pets are family members, constant companions, and sources of unconditional love. The grief experienced when losing a pet is often just as intense as losing a human loved one, and sometimes more complicated due to a lack of societal understanding."
  },
  {
    question: "How long will this grief last?",
    answer: "There is no set timeline for grief. The acute, overwhelming pain usually softens over the first few months, but feelings of loss can last for years. Healing means learning to live with the loss, not forgetting your pet."
  }
];

const relatedLinks = [
  { label: "Pet Memorial Ideas", href: "/pet-memorial-ideas/", description: "Finding ways to honor their memory can aid in the healing process." },
  { label: "At-Home Euthanasia", href: "/at-home-pet-euthanasia/", description: "Information on peaceful transition." }
];
---

<ServicePageLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  headline={headline}
  subheadline={subheadline}
  headings={headings}
  faqItems={faqItems}
  relatedLinks={relatedLinks}
  heroImageUrl="/images/pet-grief-hero.jpg"
  heroImageAlt="A person holding a dog's collar thoughtfully"
>
  <h2 id="understanding-pet-grief">Understanding Pet Grief</h2>
  <p>The bond between humans and their pets is profoundly deep and entirely unique. Because our pets rely on us completely and offer unconditional love in return, their passing leaves a massive void in our daily routines and our hearts. Validating your own feelings is the first and most important step in the grieving process. Your grief is real, and it is justified.</p>

  <h2 id="the-grieving-process">The Grieving Process is Non-Linear</h2>
  <p>You may have heard of the "stages of grief" (denial, anger, bargaining, depression, and acceptance). It's important to know that these are not neat, sequential steps. You may bounce back and forth between them, or experience several at once. You might feel okay one day and be overwhelmed by sorrow the next. This is entirely normal. Be gentle with yourself and allow yourself to feel whatever comes up.</p>

  <h2 id="supporting-children">Supporting Children Through Pet Loss</h2>
  <p>For many children, the loss of a pet is their first experience with death. It's crucial to be honest with them using age-appropriate language. Avoid euphemisms like "went to sleep" or "went to a farm," as these can cause confusion and anxiety. Encourage them to ask questions, express their sadness, and participate in memorializing the pet, perhaps by drawing a picture or helping to plant a tree.</p>

  <h2 id="when-to-seek-help">When to Seek Professional Help</h2>
  <p>While grief is a natural process, sometimes it becomes overwhelming. "Disenfranchised grief" occurs when society doesn't fully recognize the validity of the loss (which often happens with pet loss), leading to feelings of isolation. Consider seeking help from a pet loss support group or a counselor if:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Your grief is interfering with your ability to function in daily life.</li>
    <li>You are experiencing persistent feelings of guilt or depression.</li>
    <li>You feel entirely isolated and unsupported by friends or family.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>There are many hotlines and online support groups specifically dedicated to pet loss. Reaching out is a sign of strength.</p>
</ServicePageLayout>
